name: Naomi Harris
bio: Artist + photographer. Author of Haddon Hall, EUSA & America Swings. MFA 2022 UB. Used to be a caregiver, now I'm just a caring orphan.

social_posts.post_text:
50. Fucking. Years.

Had grand illusions of getting into the best shape of my life by 50 (think Linda Hamilton circa T2). Now I’m just glad I don’t need a Life Alert bracelet (yet).

📸 courtesy my Gemini twin @greggarry 

Bench by the one and only @dannyfirst at The Bunker.

#helpivefallenandicantgetup #halfcentury #serenitynow #worldsleastflatteringphoto

I was named Naomi because I was born on the holiday of Shavuot (aka the Pentecost). In the Book of Ruth, read on this day, Ruth’s mother in law is named Naomi. I pronounce it NAY-omi (like a horse) but my mother pronounced it NI-omi (like  HI 👋🏻) so I suppose you can say I’ve been mispronouncing my own name for decades.  Frankly I don’t care what you call me, just don’t call me late for dinner (bad joke courtesy of Jerry).

This was the first birthday without mum and the third without my father - I am an orphan. I did have some needless major banking headaches on my birthday (have to pay mum’s 2022 taxes and needed access to her accounts) and in the frustration of their brutal incompetence I yelled “IT’S MY 50th BIRTHDAY AND I’M AN ORPHAN!!!” Not my most stellar moment BUT I did get her taxes paid.

Instead of birthday candles I lit two yahrzeit candles for my folks, cause that’s what you do on Shavuot. All in all I had a lovely birthday (saw @gordon_shadrach phenomenal exhibition at Spadina House, went for a swim, @j3ffharris took me to see @iamjonsi give a spectacular and inspiring artist talk a few days earlier at the @agotoronto , yelled at some bank employees, received these beautiful roses from @rzhooker all the way from England, and was taken for a lovely dinner by @lavoie6467 not to mention the surprise cake she put in my fridge) but not going to lie, it was still hard. Guess it always will be a little.

#happybirthdaytome #dontcallmelatefordinner #littleorphannaomi

social_posts.post_text:
Thanks for those of you hearty Buffalonians who braved the heat and came out to @fitz_books_and_waffles for the opening of Haddon Hall. 

A lot of people told me how much they liked the way the exhibit was “hung” but honestly I can’t take credit for it…I got the idea from @juliengester (check out his lovely work) who had a wonderful exhibition in a Paris laundromat using this painters tape technique. I loved it so much and felt it really worked with these prints, so thanks for the inspiration Julien.

The show is up until June 28th so lots of time to check out the sweetest new and used book store (EXCELLENT rare and fine art section) and get a waffle and ice cream. I’ll be giving an artist talk on Tuesday June 13 @ 5 pm so mark your calendars. Let’s hope and pray it’s a heck of a lot cooler that night.

(Note NOT Maureen’s but next door at 433 Ellicott Street)

Marie and Sonja by the Pool, 1999. From the Haddon Hall series.

I'm a big fan of art seen in the wild rather than museums and galleries, and each summer @eyesonmainstreetinc brings 100 large scale photographs to the streets of Wilson, NC for a little over 3 months. What a terrific idea! Wish I could have attended the opening weekend but my wee lassie Maggie is no longer up for road trips nor am I up to leave her for long periods of time. If you're driving in the area why not make a pit stop and check out some of the work. I'm sure there's a good ol' country kitchen to visit too.

This little girl is breaking my heart one day at a time ❤️‍🩹

Those of you who know the story of how I rescued Maggie off a reservation in Saskatchewan while on a road trip across Canada July 9, 2011, also know she’s been my constant companion for nearly 12 years now. (Scroll through feed for the complete story, and put some Sarah McLaughlin music on).

When mum was diagnosed with cancer she never left her side. And since mum died in November her health has been on a steep decline. She was diagnosed with Cushing’s disease in April, which is an adrenal gland disorder and makes her hunger insatiable and constantly thirsty resulting in multiple bathroom accidents, cause as a senior dog she’s forgetting to tell me she needs to go out. I can’t leave her for longer than 4 hours anymore and haven’t slept the night through in lord knows when.

Today we visited the vet cause Saturday she was out in the backyard and got poked in the eye resulting in a cherry eye that is now infected. Expected the doctor to say she doesn’t have much time left but on the contrary. He’s upped her Cushing’s medication dose so hopefully that helps and we’ll all find a little relief. 

Maggie gets whatever she wants, when she wants it. Was supposed to travel this summer to celebrate my half a century of existence and have a bit of a break after the years of caregiving for my folks, but I’ve been grounded. My responsibility is to Maggie. I love her.

It’s been a rather emotional day for me with a lot of crying cause everyone I love keeps getting sick and leaving me. 
.
.
.
#seniordog #olddog #cushingsdisease #rescuedog #rescuedogcopilot #ilovemydog #whorescuedwho #blurdoesitbetter

First overnight assignment since 2019.

First hotel stay since before Covid.

Some things never change: bad windows so can hear all the street noise. Paper thin walls (I just heard the the person in the next room blow his nose and flush the toilet). Room several football fields away from elevators. Those weird AC/heating units you can never get quite right. The only difference is that the cost of the room is double what it was before the pandemic.

I missed this. I think. 

#istillhaveapulse #thisgunforhire #willworkforfood 
#editorialphotography #fannypacksforever

Say Naomi, what's a great way to pass the time while grieving the loss of your mum? Why not take an 8-week end-of-life doula course, a sure fire way to fun in the summertime! 

But seriously, I'm so glad I took this amazing course. Indirectly, it helped me with mourning both my folks. Directly, it's opening my eyes to perhaps what my purpose is in the next chapter of my life. 

Death. Just because you choose to ignore it doesn't mean it's going to ignore you. Best to plan while you can.

August 14, 2003, 20th anniversary of the Northeast Blackout of 2003. 

So where was I you might ask? I had *just* gotten back to my apartment at the corner of 33rd and 3rd in NYC having flown in from an assignment in Montreal. The lights flickered and voila, the blackout began. Looking out the window I saw the traffic lights out and cars at a standstill, I went downstairs to explore. Tons of people were walking the streets: some were rejoicing, others were nervous, crying, the memory of 9-11 still so fresh. 

The blackout left more than 50 million people in the northeast and most of Ontario without electricity during a heatwave. My neighbourhood didn’t get power for over 27 hours. And all this when very few people had cell phones so it meant people went outside and actually engaged with one another, restaurants and markets gave away free food before it spoiled (though some price gouged) and all in all people had a pretty good time. Doubt it would be the same today. 

But enough about the blackout, what about the assignment I had just shot….

A story about a website called “Porn Star Academie” (French sp). It was a house where amateur up and cumming porn actors lived, worked and competed for the chance to be the best new discovery. This was Survivor meets Temptation Island meets Big Brother all rolled up in a very Quebecois bow. They had live cams filming every move even while they slept. The contestants were expected to live chat with the viewers of the website…OnlyFans before its time. The assignment was for a new Canadian business magazine and I was very surprised they were ok with such a titillating story and racy photos.

Well, upon seeing the final product (I believe it was the cover story) the publisher decided they were in fact NOT ok with the story and destroyed every issue of the magazine. That must have cost a pretty penny.

Shana Tova…High Holiday issue of @thecjn out in time for tips on what shoes to wear for Yom Kippur. Did you know you are not allowed to wear leather on the Day of Atonement? That’s because we aren’t supposed to be comfortable and leather footwear was once the epitome of comfort hence we are to wear shoes made of synthetic materials. Vegan Stan Smith’s? Yes please! Comme des Garçons Cons? Absolutely! Ugg Sport Yeah? Hell yeah! 

Concept, styling, photography and text by moi.

Thanks to @ronit_novak for her terrific art direction and being my personal shopper for all these fine shoes, the superior assisting of @nessdevos, @bethemethtoronto for the location, and all the kind volunteers who loaned us their (kosher) little piggies.

Have an easy fast y’all, Gmar Tov and hope you’re all written in the good book for another year.

#kosher #fashion #yomkippur #shanatova #shoes #footfetishist

Today Jerry would have been 88, his third birthday he's missing. This photo was taken in LA April 20th, 2018 by @alysonaliano Afterwards we went to a Dodgers game, the following day we went to the track, and the next day we began our road trip back to Toronto. 7 hours into our journey (and 20 minutes from our hotel) Maggie needed a bathroom break. My father got out of the car to stretch his legs (and water a tree) and took a tumble 15 feet into a drainage ditch breaking his hip and changing all of our lives forever. 

After this incident I moved home to help mum with his care. Nine months later she was diagnosed with blood cancer so caregiving increased from one parent to two. Jerry died September 8, 2020, mum followed November 29th, 2022.

Photographs capture a moment in time that you can never go back to, but oh wouldn't it be nice to try. Happy birthday daddy...I'll be eating a hotdog in your honour. 🌭🎂🎉

social_posts.post_text: From yesterday’s The Guardian “My Best Shot." Thank you for the beautiful homage to my mama @chrisdbroughton Link to article in bio.

Today I went to the funeral of my friend’s 90-year old father. He was buried at the same cemetery as my folks so afterwards I went by to say “hi” and leave them each a Laura Secord butterscotch lollipop. I think they would have appreciated that. 

On a scale of 1 to 10, with 1 being manageable and 10 being a snotty, break down mess, I’d give today a 9.

Grief doesn’t go away, it’s always looming in the background waiting for an opportunity to pop up.

Mum in her very gory Halloween costume, 2021. 
Actually this wasn't a costume. Diane had been to a dermatologist during that summer who froze a small growth on the side of her face. But just wouldn't heal, in fact it kept getting uglier and worse. 
Flash forward a couple of months to October 30th when the spot decided to spring a leak. Mum being a nurse was very calm, cool and collected, but neither one of us could get the bleeding to stop. I called my neighbour who is a GP and she couldn't stop the bleeding either so we went to the ER. Shockingly it wasn't busy considering it was a weekend. They placed mum in a room quickly (being immunocompromised she couldn't be around other people and also she was literally bleeding through everything). The doctor gave her a couple of stitches and finally stopped the bloodbath that had been going nonstop for the past 3 hours. 
Mum had a wicked sense of humour. Never complained, only made light out of the situation. I mean here's a woman with myelodysplastic syndrome, a rare form of blood cancer, literally bleeding out and she's still cracking jokes. 
The stitches held up for two days before she started bleeding again. I was away at school in Buffalo when she called me at 7 am to say that a trickle of blood was running down her face and she wasn't sure what to do. I told her to call a friend to take her back to the dermatology department to see the original doctor who did this to her in the first place. There it took a team of 6 doctors and nurses over 3 hours to stop the bleeding, afterwards she received a transfusion while I made the drive back to Toronto to pick her up. 
Sadly, they did a biopsy on the site of the wound and discovered leukemic cells, which explained why her face wasn't healing. Having progressed to leukemia meant her treatments ended and they tried something new (which didn't work). Ultimately she spent nearly a year receiving blood and platelet transfusions twice a week to keep going. If you're B+ and donate blood or are a platelet donor, there's a strong chance Diane got some of it, so thank you. 
This event was the catalyst for my thesis piece "anticipatory GRIEF" but I'll save that for another time.

Naomi Harris is a Canadian photographer living in Toronto. Harris studied at the International Center of Photography in New York, where she later taught several courses. A few of her personal projects were shot while on road trips, resulting in solo exhibitions and accompanying books. Her work has also been published in the New York Times Magazine, the London Sunday Times Magazine, The Telegraph Magazine, Marie Claire UK, Vice, and Newsweek. 

You can find three of her images, shown here at our print sale, with all proceeds donated to Israeli Kibbutzim survivors.

Today mum would have turned 84. This video was taken a couple of days after her 83rd birthday (she was in the hospital on her actual birthday with a fever). We decided to celebrate her birthday everyday from then on cause why not celebrate this angel daily. Sadly we didn’t get to sing happy birthday that many more times as she died 20 days later. I can’t believe it’s nearly a year since you and your little squeaky voice left. I miss you every day mummy.

☀️Good morning!☀️
The last of mum’s flowers of 2023 before the frost set in (fox glove, pin cushion, lavender). Displayed in my demented sun bud vase. 
This summer I (like every other artist) decided to dip my toe into ceramics and I love it. Don’t get me wrong, I I love photography, but it’s so cerebral and equipment reliant. Sure you can design your narrative through research, building sets and heavily staging your photographs, but there is something primordial and grounding with working with your hands in clay. And I don’t worry if it’s any good or “professional” looking, in fact I love the childlike roughness and handmade quality of the pieces I’m making. There’s also a real therapeutic quality working with clay, great way to work out your aggressions by squeezing and pounding. 
More TK.
.
.
.
#ceramics #pottery #handmade #demented #sun

Today is my mother’s first yahrzeit, or the anniversary of her death, according to the Hebrew/lunar calendar. I didn’t actually know it was until a cousin from Israel emailed me so I didn’t light the candle until kind of late. I’ll be observing her English death-day which is in 10 days. 

iPhones have this feature where it shows you a photo they think you want to see. Sometimes it’s a pleasant surprise, sometimes it’s a punch in the gut. Today’s photo is this picture of Mum and Maggs the first autumn she had cancer. I remember after her treatment we went to the woods nearby to walk amongst the fall leaves. It was the first time she got winded while walking and the start of her not being her same old self. Both her and Maggie look healthy here, that’s the way I like to remember them.

Today’s photo that my iPhone decided I should remember was taken July 13, 2020. 

My father Jerry is demonstrating his mobility to an occupational therapist over Zoom because, well, don’t you remember, we were still in lockdown thanks to Covid. My mum Diane looks on. 
After a small fall in the kitchen a few weeks earlier in May, my father kept having little falls and his mobility was worsening by the day. Unable to meet with anyone in person we resorted to an online appointment where he could barely hear her instructions but hey, it was better than nothing. Of course he didn’t do the exercises the OT gave him and in just over a month he was to develop a UTI that would land him in the hospital leading to the brood the end. 

It’s amazing what memories photos unleash when we have the time and distance from the moment it was taken. Ok Apple, I’m ready for you, what depressing memory do you have in store for me tomorrow??

#iphotoreminder #iphone #featuredphoto #gutpunch #hitmewithyourbestshot

At approximately this time last year you took your last breath. When you awoke that morning we didn’t have a clue that it was to be your last day on planet earth. Not that it was sudden, after all you had been living with  myelodysplastic syndrome (MDS) for 2 and a half years and then leukaemia for nearly another. But it came out of left field considering you were getting ready to leave for your blood transfusion when you had that first stroke. 

But I don’t want to remember you as you were that last day, I prefer to think of you enjoying a warm May day, observing the progress of your garden, enjoying an ice cream sandwich. 

It was an honour to be with you on your journey mum. I miss you every day more than I imagined possible. 

You got the Feature Photo right today iPhone.

👩💋🎅🏻🎄

From my book “America Swings.”

As people post their greatest achievements of 2023 I’d say mine are that I managed to get dressed (and brush my teeth) most days, swim occasionally and discover the joy of pottery. Didn’t have any massively big shoots, heck don’t know if people know I even still photograph. No big retrospective shows or big write ups. No books or other massive accomplishments. And that’s ok. The fact that I am sitting with my grief and figuring out where I’m going to move too and what’s next in life is where I’m at today, and it may be where you are too. I see you and there are more of us out there so it’s ok to not be ok.

The problem with social media is it encourages us to always be happy happy happy even when we’re crumbling and are a bowl of jello on he insides. But no one wants to know the truth just like when someone asks “how are you?” and you answer “not so great actually” and they reply “terrific, me too!” Seriously try it sometime, most people are not really listening to your response. 

I will continue to live in my “negative” curmudgeon way amongst all this toxic positivity cause that’s what life actually is. And you can either embrace it head on or put on a mask of “everything is ok!”…either way you’re going to feel rotten. 

But at least try to embrace the humour in life and our situations. And wear cowboy boots without pants. 

Here’s to 2024…it honestly has got to be better. Right? RIGHT?!
